n  <i>Piperellus</i>), a diminutive of Old French  <i>pevre</i> ‘pepper’ (Anglo-Norman French  <i>peivere</i>, Latin  <i>piper</i>), originally perhaps used as a nickname on the Continent but used as a personal name in Anglo-Norman England."]}]},{"name":"Laura","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Feminine form of the Late Latin male name <i>Laurus</i> ‘laurel’.  St Laura  was a 9th-century Spanish nun who met her death in a cauldron of molten lead. Laura is also the name of the woman addressed in the love poetry of the Italian poet  Petrarch  (  Francesco Petrarca ,  1304–74 ), and it owes much of its subsequent popularity to this. There have been various speculations about her identity, but it has not been established with any certainty. He first met her in  1327  while living in Avignon, and she died of the plague in  1348 . The popularity of the given name in the English-speaking world has endured since the 19th century, when it was probably imported from Italy."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Laura Peverell was born about 1273, in Devon, England, United Kingdom. She married Sir Hugh Raleigh about 1289, in Smallridge, Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"ABT 1273–":"umbes 1273–Surnud","1270–1303":"1270–1303","1295–1340":"1295–1340","1273–Female":"1273–Surnud","Bef 1295":"enne 1295","ABT 1273":"umbes 1273","1303":"1303","Abt 1289":"umbes 1289","1340":"1340","1273":"1273","1295":"1295","1270":"1270","Ermynton, Devonshire, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Axminster, , Devonshire, England":"Axminster, Devon, England","Smallridge, Devon, England":"Smallridge, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ABT 1273–":"noin 1273–Kuollut","1270–1303":"1270–1303","1295–1340":"1295–1340","1273–Female":"1273–Kuollut","Bef 1295":"ennen vuotta 1295","ABT 1273":"noin 1273","1303":"1303","Abt 1289":"noin 1289","1340":"1340","1273":"1273","12